AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp;In Israel, the head of the military intelligence Aharon Haliva resigned, > for the errors and omissions of the secret services in thwarting Hamas' attack on 7 October last year. The news was anticipated by Israeli daily Yedioth Ahronoth.<br> "We did not respect our task. Since then, I've been taking me on that black day, day and night. I will always bring with me the terrible pain of the war," he wrote in a letter to the chief of state, asking, however, the establishment of a commission of inquiry.<br> Haliva had already assumed responsibility for the errors committed > about a week and a half after the outbreak of the war. In the letter to Lieutenant General Herzi Halevi, Haliva did not specify what was wrong. It is not clear when resignations become operational because Israel must now find a substitute.
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The army > made known that General Aharon Haliva "will keep his mandate and withdraw &nbsp; from the Israeli Defense Forces, once he appointed his successor".<br> Haliva thus became the first senior official to resign due to the errors that allowed the bloody attack, errors that also led to an internal investigation by the army at the end of February,
<br> Already in October, Haliva, who is 38 years of service in the Israeli Defense Forces, had taken part in the blame of what happened: not only did not thwart the attack, but also the slow response of the military, which at least at first did very little against the thousands of Hamas> terrorists, who that day took control of a dozen Israeli communities and occupied armed 3% of the territory. The internal investigation is precisely trying to analyze the response of the troops, even in the previous and after the attack, as well as their deployment on the ground and the operating procedures used to neutralize the militians. According to a survey published today and conducted between 14 and 17 April by the Israel Democracy Institute, 62% of the Israeli population - both Jews and Arabs - believes that the time has come for those responsible for the failures of 7 October, more than six months from the massacre, to resign.&nbsp;

