AGI -&nbsp;In 2023 Europe recorded a record number of days when the heat felt was "extreme" for the human body, due to temperatures greater than 35 C or 40 C whose effects on organisms were accentuated by moisture, absence of wind or heat of urban concrete. This is what emerges from the report published on World Earth Day by the European Copernicus Observatory and the World Meteorological Organization of the UN.
&nbsp;
"The year 2023 has reached a record number of days of 'extreme thermal stress', that is, days when the perceived temperature exceeded the equivalent of 46 degrees," reads in the report. In addition to the hot waves, the continent has undergone many extreme weather events during the year: Two million people were affected by floods or storms, severe droughts hit the Iberian Peninsula and Eastern Europe and the largest forest fire in the history of the continent devastated 96,000 hectares over the year. These disasters cost €13.4 billion, 80% attributable to floods in a year characterized by rainfall well above the average.
&nbsp;
This year the UN, which in English calls her "mother earth's day", emphasizes that "Mother Earth is clearly urging an invitation to action. Nature is suffering. The oceans fill in plastic and become more acidic. The extreme heat, fires and floods hit millions of people. Climate change, natural changes caused by man and crimes that destroy biodiversity, such as deforestation, change in land use, intensification of agriculture and livestock production or the growing illegal trade of wild species, can speed up the speed of destruction of the planet."
&nbsp;
The UN also recalls that today's "is the third Earth Day celebrated within the UN Decade for Restoration of Ecosystems. Ecosystems support the whole life on Earth. The healthier our ecosystems, the healthier the planet and its inhabitants. Restoration of our damaged ecosystems will help to end poverty, combat climate change and prevent mass extinction. But we're only going to make it if everyone contributes," it's the UN appeal.&nbsp;

